23 outside the United States by electronic or other means. The term
24 "money received for transmission" has a corresponding meaning.
25 (28) "Stored value" means monetary value representing a claim,
26 against the issuer, that is evidenced by an electronic or digital
27 record and that is intended and accepted for use as a means of
28 redemption for money or monetary value, or payment for goods
29 or services. The term includes "prepaid access" as defined in 31
30 CFR 1010.100. The term does not include:
31 (A) a payment instrument;
32 (B) closed loop stored value; or
33 (C) stored value not sold to the public but issued and
34 distributed as part of a loyalty, rewards, or promotional
35 program.
36 (29) "Tangible net worth" means the aggregate assets of a
37 licensee, excluding all intangible assets, less liabilities, as
38 determined in accordance with United States generally accepted
39 accounting principles.
40 SECTION 3. IC 28-8-7 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE AS
41 A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE UPON
42 PASSAGE]:
HB 1116—LS 6503/DI 119

12
1 Chapter 7. Virtual Currency Kiosks
2 Sec. 1. This chapter does not apply to the following:
3 (1) A federally insured depository financial institution (as
4 defined in IC 28-8-4.1-201(11)).
5 (2) A bank holding company.
6 (3) An office of an international banking corporation.
7 (4) A foreign bank that establishes a federal branch under the
8 International Banking Act of 1978 (12 U.S.C. 3101 et seq.).
9 (5) A corporation organized under the Bank Service Company
10 Act (12 U.S.C. 1861 et seq.).
11 (6) A corporation organized under the Edge Act (12 U.S.C.
12 611 et seq.).
13 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "blockchain" means data that is:
14 (1) shared across a network to create a ledger of verified
15 transactions or information among network participants; and
16 (2) linked using cryptography to maintain the integrity of the
17 ledger and to execute other functions.
18 Sec. 3. As used in this chapter, "blockchain analytics" means the
19 examination and interpretation of data extracted from public
20 records of transactions on blockchains or on similar publicly
21 distributed electronic ledgers.
22 Sec. 4. As used in this chapter, "blockchain analytics and
23 tracing software" means a software service that uses blockchain
24 analytics to provide:
25 (1) risk specific information regarding blockchain
26 transactions; and
27 (2) tracing of virtual currency addresses.
28 Sec. 5. As used in this chapter, "charges", with respect to a
29 virtual currency transaction, means:
30 (1) fees or expenses paid by a user to the operator of a virtual
31 currency kiosk as compensation for the operator's facilitation
32 of the virtual currency transaction; and
33 (2) the difference between:
34 (A) the market price of a virtual currency purchased, sold,
35 transferred, or exchanged by the user in the virtual
36 currency transaction; and
37 (B) the price of the virtual currency charged to the user by
38 the operator of the virtual currency kiosk.
39 Sec. 6. As used in this chapter, "operate", with regard to a
40 virtual currency kiosk, means to use the virtual currency kiosk to
41 remotely conduct or facilitate virtual currency transactions
42 through the virtual currency kiosk:
HB 1116—LS 6503/DI 119

13
1 (1) on behalf of users of the virtual currency kiosk; and
2 (2) for compensation by a user of the virtual currency kiosk
3 in the form of charges assessed to the user.
4 Sec. 7. As used in this chapter, "operator", with regard to a
5 virtual currency kiosk, means a person that:
6 (1) owns; or
7 (2) engages in the business of operating;
8 the virtual currency kiosk, regardless of whether the person
9 provides custodial or noncustodial services with regard to virtual
10 currency.
11 Sec. 8. As used in this chapter, "user" means an individual that
12 initiates a virtual currency transaction through a virtual currency
13 kiosk for the purpose of the individual's purchase, sale, transfer, or
14 exchange of virtual currency.
15 Sec. 9. As used in this chapter, "virtual currency" means a
16 natively electronic asset that:
17 (1) confers economic, proprietary, or access rights or powers;
18 and
19 (2) is recorded using cryptographically secured distributed
20 ledger technology, or an analogous technology.
21 Sec. 10. As used in this chapter, "virtual currency address"
22 means an alphanumeric identifier that is associated with a virtual
23 currency wallet and that identifies the location to which a virtual
24 currency transaction can be sent.
25 Sec. 11. As used in this chapter, "virtual currency kiosk" means
26 an electronic terminal through which the operator of the electronic
27 terminal is able to conduct or facilitate a virtual currency
28 transaction on behalf of a third party, including by:
29 (1) connecting to a separate virtual currency exchange that
30 performs the transaction; or
31 (2) drawing on virtual currency in the possession of the
32 operator.
33 Sec. 12. As used in this chapter, "virtual currency transaction"
34 means:
35 (1) an exchange of virtual currency for:
36 (A) money;
37 (B) bank credit; or
38 (C) another form of virtual currency; or
39 (2) an exchange of:
40 (A) money; or
41 (B) bank credit;
42 for virtual currency;
HB 1116—LS 6503/DI 119

14
1 conducted through a virtual currency kiosk.
2 Sec. 13. As used in this chapter, "virtual currency transaction
3 hash" means a unique, alphanumeric identifier that:
4 (1) is assigned to a transaction on a blockchain; and
5 (2) confirms that the transaction has been validated and
6 added to the blockchain.
7 Sec. 14. As used in this chapter, "virtual currency wallet" means
8 a software application or other mechanism providing a means to
9 hold the electronic keys necessary to access and transfer virtual
10 currency.
11 Sec. 15. After December 31, 2026, a person may not operate a
12 virtual currency kiosk that is located in Indiana unless the person
13 is licensed under IC 28-8-4.1.
14 Sec. 16. A person may not install, or cause a third party to
15 install, a virtual currency kiosk in Indiana unless the person:
16 (1) is licensed under IC 28-8-4.1, after December 31, 2026;
17 and
18 (2) obtains authorization for the installation from the
19 department.
